vectorData.altText: IDENTIFY other major features of the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere.

The diencephalon includes the thalamus, hypothalamus and the epithalamus. The key to identifying the components of the diencephalon is to use three structures as landmarks. Identify the optic chiasm     , the mammillary body     , and the anterior commissure     . These
three landmarks define the corners of a triangle enclosing the hypothalamus. Identify the location of the pituitary stalk between the optic chiasma and the mammillary body.
the point of decussation (crossing the midline) of the optic nerves
a bundle of axons connecting the two temporal lobes

Identify the hypothalamic sulcus, a groove superoposterior to a line joining the anterior commissure and the mammillary body. This is the border between the hypothalamus, below, and the thalamus above.
Identify the pineal gland posterior to the thalamus. It is the largest, and most identifiable feature of the epithalamus     .
Medial view of the right cerebral hemisphere. From Serial Dissections of the Human Brainby Carlton G. Smith, M.D., Ph.D.

Because it is an unpaired midline structure, the pineal gland might not be present on your half brain. If not, look for it on another half brain in your lab. You can also see the pineal gland on the whole brain by gently opening the transverse fissure between the occipital lobe and the cerebellum.
